📖 Theory
What is a User?

Every person or application in Linux runs as a user.

Examples:

root
ubuntu
jenkins
nginx
mysql
What is a Group?

Groups simplify permission management.

Example:

Developers
├── sachin
├── john
└── alice
🛠️ Task 1 – View Current User
whoami

Check user details:

id
🛠️ Task 2 – View All Users
cat /etc/passwd

Human-readable list:

cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd
🛠️ Task 3 – View Groups
cat /etc/group

Current user's groups:

groups
🛠️ Task 4 – Create a User
sudo adduser devopsuser

Verify:

id devopsuser
🛠️ Task 5 – Delete a User

Keep home directory:

sudo deluser devopsuser

Delete home directory:

sudo deluser --remove-home devopsuser
🛠️ Task 6 – Create a Group
sudo groupadd devops

Verify:

getent group devops
🛠️ Task 7 – Add User to Group
sudo usermod -aG devops sachin

Replace sachin with your Linux username.

Verify:

groups
🛠️ Task 8 – Sudo Access

Grant sudo:

sudo usermod -aG sudo devopsuser

Verify:

sudo -l
🛠️ Task 9 – Lock & Unlock User

Lock:

sudo passwd -l devopsuser

Unlock:

sudo passwd -u devopsuser
🛠️ Task 10 – Password Expiration

Check:

sudo chage -l devopsuser

Force password change:

sudo chage -d 0 devopsuser
